com.dsi.ant.plugins
Class ThirdPartyDeviceProviderMsgDefines.DeviceAccessRequest.RequestAccessMessage

java.lang.Object
  com.dsi.ant.plugins.ThirdPartyDeviceProviderMsgDefines.DeviceAccessRequest.RequestAccessMessage
Enclosing class:
ThirdPartyDeviceProviderMsgDefines.DeviceAccessRequest
public class ThirdPartyDeviceProviderMsgDefines.DeviceAccessRequest.RequestAccessMessage
extends java.lang.Object

After receiving information for provided device(s) from the provider, if desired, the client can request access to a specific device. This allows the client and the provider to exchange information necessary to fully initialize and setup the API communication to access and utilize the device. This message is sent on the ThirdPartyDeviceProviderMsgDefines.RequestForDevices.RequestList_ResponseMessage.PARAM_msgrACCESSREQUESTRECEIVER sent in the originally provided device information.

PARAM_bundleANTDEVICEPARAMS

public static final java.lang.String PARAM_bundleANTDEVICEPARAMS
Key to the bundle containing the expected device parameters of the device the client is requesting. These parameters will match the initial search request, but they are resent in this request for convenience in case the provider needs to perform additional initialization to match the device requirements.

PARAM_stringREQUESTERDISPLAYNAME

public static final java.lang.String PARAM_stringREQUESTERDISPLAYNAME
Key to a display friendly name of the client. The requester includes this value to allow the provider to display the source of the request. Possible uses of this name could be to use in a confirmation prompt to grant access, or in a list keeping track of all clients using devices. Note: The client may or may not be the same as the requester. The 'client' refers to the code that is utilizing the device. For example, if a heart rate graphing application is using the ANT+ Heart Rate plugin to get data, the graphing application is the client, but the ANT+ plugin is the requester because it will perform the actual request on behalf of the client.

See Also:
